      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(whatsapp): thread authDir through command authorization and owner bypass for LID JID resolution",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n- WhatsApp group commands (`/new`, `/stop`) can be silently ignored when Baileys reports the sender as a LID JID (`@lid`) instead of a phone JID (`@s.whatsapp.net`)\n- Root cause: `resolveWhatsAppCommandAuthorized()` and `isOwnerSender()` called `getSelfIdentity()`/`getSenderIdentity()` without passing `authDir`, so the LID-to-phone reverse mapping could not happen and the sender was treated as unauthorized\n- Thread `account.authDir` through both command authorization and group owner-bypass identity resolution paths, enabling proper LID JID → phone E.164 resolution before owner/allowlist checks\n- Rebased onto latest `main` — resolved merge conflicts in `inbound-policy.ts` and `group-gating.ts` (keep `AdmittedWebInboundMessage` type + add `authDir` parameter)\n\n## Verification\n\n- `pnpm test extensions/whatsapp/src/inbound/access-control.test.ts` — 16/16 passed\n- `pnpm check:changed` — pending\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\nBehavior addressed: WhatsApp group commands from LID JID senders are now properly authorized through authDir-backed LID-to-phone reverse mapping.\nReal environment tested: Linux, Node 22, branch `fix/issue-77755-whatsapp-lid-authdir` commit `845f4d798a`\nExact steps or command run after this patch:\n```bash\nnode scripts/run-vitest.mjs extensions/whatsapp/src/inbound/access-control.test.ts\n```\nEvidence after fix:\n```console\n$ node scripts/run-vitest.mjs extensions/whatsapp/src/inbound/access-control.test.ts\n\n RUN  v4.1.8\n\n Test Files  1 passed (1)\n      Tests  16 passed (16)\n```\nObserved result after fix: All 16 tests pass including the new LID sender regression test with a simulated reverse mapping file.\nWhat was not tested: Live WhatsApp account E2E (requires Crabbox with WhatsApp auth); no WhatsApp binary/E2E test infrastructure exists.\n",
